The Presidential Memorandum addresses the need to expand broadband deployment and adoption in the United States. It emphasizes that access to high-speed broadband is essential for economic growth and competitiveness. The memorandum directs executive departments and agencies to use their authorities to identify and address regulatory barriers, encourage investment in broadband networks and services, promote the adoption and use of broadband technology, and support broadband deployment and competition. The memorandum establishes the Broadband Opportunity Council, which will be responsible for coordinating the efforts of various government agencies and stakeholders. The Council will identify regulatory barriers, assess funding opportunities, and develop recommendations for actions to support broadband deployment and adoption. The memorandum also includes general provisions, stating that it does not affect existing laws or authorities, protect classified information, or require duplicate efforts. It emphasizes that the memorandum does not create any legally enforceable rights or benefits.